The *Explanation* reads: "而人不知接之之道," noting that one version omits the character "人." The sage is all-knowing and all-penetrating, thus able to lead and employ them. The wisdom of beasts includes what comes naturally and what they share with human children. In aligning desires and preserving life, they do not borrow wisdom from humans:

Male and female pair as mates, mother and child share affection; they avoid flatlands and seek high ground, shun cold and pursue warmth;

chunks.translated_text:
The River Bend Wise Old Man laughed and sought to dissuade him. {Note: Though commonly called wise, he was not necessarily free from folly.} He said, “How extreme is your lack of wisdom! With your waning years and remaining strength, you cannot even destroy a single blade of grass on the mountain—what then can you do with the earth and stones?”

The Old Fool of North Mountain sighed deeply and said, “Your heart is so obstinate that it cannot be penetrated. {Pei Jun notes: *Che* means ‘to penetrate.’ *Shiwen* reads: *che*, *chou lie* cut.} You are not even the equal of a widow or a weak child. Though I should die, I have a son who remains. {Wang Chongmin notes: *Yuwenzhui* 519 cites *cun* as *zai*.} The son will beget a grandson, the grandson will beget a son; the son will have a son, the son will have a grandson: sons and grandsons will have no end, yet the mountain will not grow larger—why then should we not level it?” All editions of the *Daoist Canon* read: “How could it not be leveled?” {Wang Chongmin notes: The *Shiwen* edition and *Jifu* edition read *ku* as *ruo*, which is correct; the error likely arose from their graphic similarity. *Yuwenzhui* 40 includes the character *ke* above *ping*. *Shiwen* reads *ku* as *ruo*, noting: *ruo* is an alternate reading for *ku*.}

The River Bend Wise Old Man had no reply. {Note: His reasoning was defeated, and his will subdued.}

With every melody Bo Ya played, Zhong Ziqi invariably fathomed its essence. Thereupon Bo Ya set down his qin and sighed, *Shiwen* glosses: 舍, pronounced *shě*. "Excellent! Excellent indeed is your listening! Your intent and imagination are as my own heart." {Annotation: This speaks of a hidden accord, no different from his own.} *Shiwen* glosses: 夫, pronounced *fú*. "Where can I conceal my sound from you?" {Annotation: Once the sound is uttered, Zhong Ziqi has already grasped his heart—thus there is no place to hide his sound.}

{Exegesis: The formation of sound arises from and moves through resonance; the arising of the heart, sound follows in its wake. Thus the five senses all communicate, all transmitted by the discerning mind. One adept at listening can know even a sigh or a cough—how much more so when sound is formed through pattern? How could it not be distinguished?}

Qin Enfu notes: Lu’s exegesis reads "discerning mind" as "mind’s discernment."

Bo Jun’s note: The *Taiping Yulan* (1) cites the *Fuzi*: "When Bo Ya traveled to the northern slopes of Mount Tai, he encountered a violent storm and took shelter beneath a cliff. He took up his qin and played, performing the *Linyu* melody, then composing the sound of crumbling mountains. With every melody he played, Zhong Ziqi invariably fathomed its essence. He said: 'Excellent indeed is your listening!'"

